* Not all grocery stores are enforcing the social distancing guidelines. For instance, 2 weeks ago, my local Ralphs had everyone wait in line outside before security guards would intermittently allow in around 20 customers at a time. Yet, in that line, there was no one to ensure customers were maintaining distance from one another. (And most were standing within 2 ft of each other.) When I went back to Ralphs the next week, there was no such crowd control and customers were not maintaining a 6-ft distance inside. At one point I was in the produce section and an Instacart driver came right up to where I was standing (less than 2 ft away), seemingly oblivious. And people were cramped toward the checkout area as well.
* There are also some grocery stores that inherently small, which don't easily facilitate social distancing.

* Contrary to the data posted about LA County on this site's map, religious gatherings are not happening.

Might be interesting to know when masks have been required in public places.  Starting on April 13, grocery stores began to require that all customers are masked.  

Also, Hawaii County is the entire island of Hawaii which is bigger than Delaware or Rhode Island.  So nine-digit zip code data might be valuable for analytical purposes when analyzing cases.

Apparently the weeks with "no new cases", and the fact that we have not had any deaths reported in Hawaii County have caused an alarming lax in concern by many individuals. comments: Several of the questions on this survey are worded in a misleading manner. For example, when I answer that "I have been within 6 feet of someone else I do not live with within the past day" this suggests that social distancing is not being followed. However the frequency of ~6 foot interactions has dropped dramatically. It would be easy to infer false conclusions based on the answers to these questions
My father was diagnosed with Covid-19 and I flew here from California to be with my mom.

Most of the people I see are being very cautious. For example, when walking, they would move off the sidewalk and into the street, at least 6 feet, but often close to 12 feet. Maybe 10% of people I see are less cautious when out walking/running/biking. I have seen one specific neighbor whose child rides bikes with another neighborhood child every day. Those children are not maintaining a distance of 6 feet. Additionally, one neighbor has a nanny who comes daily to care for her kids, although there is one parent not working and who is not an essential worker.
The areas where people are not respecting the 6' are outdoor jogging/running/hiking paths, campus paths, etc.

People is my neighborhood I’d say are very conscientious. However, this perspective is perhaps skewed because it is a neighborhood of stand-alone homes with yards and several parks. Less than a mile away is the campus of EMU, and students forced to continue living in communal situations with little private outdoor space are likely having a very different experience.

Generally speaking, residents of my city, Canby, have been willing to social distance and have taken the pandemic seriously. Canby City government closed on March 13th, which included all public buildings (library, aquatic center etc.) and have yet to reopen. Local churches advertise online services on their reader boards and even the local veterinarian has switched to "drive thru" services - asking owners to call ahead for 'curbside pick up' of food, medications and treatments. We have a large population in the city of elderly & retired individuals, including a large retirement and assisted living community. I would like to think that we are aware of our vulnerable neighbors. 

I work at the City of Wilsonville, which is also within Clackamas County. Our buildings have been closed to the public since March 17th, remaining open to provide essential services. Some employees have been approved to work remotely, but most are required to be present on site. City government closures have varied in the area - Canby closed their administrative offices, but cities like Wilsonville, West Linn, Molalla, and Lake Oswego have remained 'open' - buildings closed to the public with some employees working remotely but essential services are uninterrupted.

I've been laid off from my nonessential job because of the virus, since March 19, same day as the PA governor order to close "non-life sustaining" businesses at the end of that day. His first attempt was  askingaiming voluntary compliance of "non-essential businesses" to close, hoping people would voluntarily comply (that did not happen), plus there was confusion as to what was "non-essential").  PA's governor then extended the deadline for that mandatory order to close non life sustaining businesses to Monday, March 23. The order has been in place since. I have not gone out to look for another job while laid off (I work at a tshirt shop in the production side...no way to work from home) because I want to take myself out of circulation to help society get a better handle on this virus. My girlfriend, who I do not live with, works from home for her full time job, but works 2 days a week at Aldi supermarket in a suburb of Pittsburgh, she observes the stores being crowded and people not always following 6 feet social distance. Because of this (and local supermarket - esp Giant Eagle - testing positive, her Aldi supermarket and Giant Eagle stores (I think all Giant Eagle, Pittsburgh's biggest supermarket chain) are enacting numerical limits on people being allowed in stores. As for me and my girlfriend, we are only spending time every few days but staying 6 or more feet apart. I am not spending any time with family or friends.

comments: I go out to walk daily but otherwise don't go out but once every 10-14 days for groceries and I believe most in my neighborhood do the same. But, as far as the county goes, some young people (teenagers) do not take the restrictions seriously and don't follow the 6ft social distancing guidelines.

People in central Vermont where I live seem to be abiding by the rules. Three weeks ago my wife and I returned from a two month trip traveling by car to the West Coast. On our return, the State was was requiring folks returning from outside the state to quarantine for two weeks. Yesterday was my first visit out of the house in around three weeks. I was happy to see that Hannaford's, our local food store, had created a safe environment. All aisles were clearly marked one way, checkout aisles were marked with large circles at six foot intervals, and an employee was enforcing the requirement and directing people to available checkouts. Areas that usually involve contact between staff and shoppers (i.e. deli counter, fresh fish and meat counter) were closed. Items usually purchased there were prepackaged. I would estimate that 90 to 95% of shoppers were masked and many also wore gloves. All staff wore protection. Reusable bags were allowed only if you bagged them yourself and had to be filled while in your shopping cart. Employees enforced the rules and people complied without questioning the rationale. However, the six foot rule was difficult to adhere. I live in a very rural area and stores typically are uncrowded. (one of the plusses among many) It must be very difficult in urban areas to stay six feet apart in a grocery store.
I was not entirely sure about all of this

In response, access to the National Park has been increasingly locked down. The "been heres" are more financially at risk and have the least access to healthcare.  Both the been/come here's are trying very hard to adhere to distancing.  Delays in seeking essential medical care (chest pain, difficulty breathing, other serious illnesses) are common. The last couple of questions were extremely subjective.  It's difficult to answer with any modicum of unbias accuracy, due to the limited time I've spent out in public. Our Superintendent made it very clear early on that we as a school district should prepare for a probable shutdown and move to alternative teaching methods.

I live in a town adjacent to the town where the outbreak bean here in the US, so local and state reactions have been fast and comprehensive.  Our school district was the first in the nation to close and the first to embrace the distance learning experiment before the Governor declared a SOE and paused all educational efforts.  Now that the state school superintendent has instituted plans at the state level, we have resumed distance learning, but we expect school to remain physically closed the rest of the school year (June 2020).

In looking around my town, it seems that most people are trying to follow social distancing. However, we have a large student population (Western Washington University is in the town) and it seems that many of these young people are socializing in small groups. Perhaps they all live together- college apartments often have many people in them- but it does seem that younger folks are less strict in following the protocols. Most people I talk to also seem to be genuinely trying to follow the order, but a little confused regarding what we should really be doing. Can I bike ride with a friend if we stay six feet apart? Should I be sanitizing my groceries' packaging? Could passing someone on the sidewalk cause a transmission? Grocery stores seem to be the hardest place to maintain distance. Also, since my town is not too far from Seattle, it all feels closer to home and people are trying to socially distance themselves correctly. Additionally, it seems that the fear of unknowingly infecting someone else is a greater motivator than the fear of getting sick yourself. Thank you all for doing this important research and work! Also- Hi Uncle Stephen! From your niece Leigh, who is currently living in Washington. :)
